{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01KBkKfdDDsktBPdf5YigF2w","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The annotations are correctly set. But the nginx config still shows `limit_req_status 503;` in the global http block. Let me look at lines around 85 to 210 to understand the nginx config structure and see if the status code was correctly propagated.\n\nActually, let me look at how nginx-ingress handles the `limit-status-code` annotation. Looking at the nginx-ingress source code:\n\nThe `limit-status-code` annotation sets the global `limit_req_status` directive in the `http` block. However, the default is 503. If the annotation is set to 429 on an ingress, it should change this global value.\nI'm wondering if the issue is that the `rate-api-alt-easy` decoy ingress without the annotation is causing the controller to fall back to the default 503 status code, or perhaps the controller was restarted before the annotation change took effect.\n\nLooking at the timestamps more carefully, the reload at 21:49:15 corresponds to when I added the annotation, and then there's a validation message at 21:50:06 that suggests another configuration update might have happened. I should verify whether the nginx config actually got reloaded with the new status code setting.\n\nActually, I'm realizing that `limit_req_status` might be a global directive in nginx-ingress that applies across the entire http block rather than per-location, which could mean the annotation alone isn't enough. There's likely a ConfigMap option like `limit-req-status-code` that controls this globally, so let me check if I can set it there instead.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":770,"cache_read_input_tokens":43784,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":770},"output_tokens":18,"service_tier":"standard","infe