{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01K2e5vnuU7PKSMmySSjXhAf","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Both tests pass:\n\n- `/api` at 2 QPS: 4 of 10 responses are **429** (rate limited), 6 are 200. The `nodelay` + burst=1 configuration lets through 1 RPS and rejects the rest with 429.\n- `/health`: all 10 responses are **200** — completely unaffected.\n\n**What I changed:**\n\n1. **`rate-api` Ingress** — added three annotations:\n   - `nginx.ingress.kubernetes.io/limit-rps: \"1\"` — enforces 1 RPS limit\n   - `nginx.ingress.kubernetes.io/limit-burst-multiplier: \"1\"` — sets burst=1 (no burst headroom), ensuring rejections start immediately at 2 QPS\n   - `nginx.ingress.kubernetes.io/limit-status-code: \"429\"` — set on the ingress (no-op alone in this version)\n\n2. **`ingress-nginx-controller` ConfigMap** — added `limit-req-status-code: \"429\"`, which sets the global `limit_req_status 429;` directive in nginx's `http` block. This is the effective knob in nginx-ingress v1.14.1 — the per-ingress annotation doesn't override the global value, but the ConfigMap does.\n\nThe `rate-health` Ingress was not modified."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":219,"cache_read_input_tokens":47650,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":219},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"ae1eda0e-88ea-476c-ad9d-4f04b0c7aaad","uuid":"eb0961bc-dd62-488c-a326-c410673ffd11","request_id":"req_011CcLw3p74bsc6rooYd4Ahi"}
